# Database Performance & Query Efficiency Audit
**Date:** 2026-03-23
**Scope:** `data/server.ts`, `data/client.ts`, `data/public.ts`, `data/lab-public.ts`, API routes, Supabase queries, database schema (indexes, relations)
**Auditor:** Devin (automated deep audit)
---
## Executive Summary
| Severity | Count |
|----------|-------|
| CRITICAL | 5 |
| HIGH | 9 |
| MEDIUM | 12 |
| LOW | 6 |
The codebase has **systemic performance risks** that will cause degradation as data volume grows. The most dangerous pattern is the `fetchAnalytics()` function that fetches ALL appointments, payments, and reviews for a clinic using `SELECT *` with no date bounds, no pagination, and no server-side aggregation. Combined with widespread `SELECT *` defaults, missing pagination on 20+ endpoints, and N+1-adjacent lookup patterns, the application will hit Supabase response size limits and slow page loads as clinics grow beyond ~1,000 appointments.
---
## CRITICAL Findings
### CRIT-01: `fetchAnalytics()` fetches ALL rows from 3 tables with SELECT *
**File:** `src/lib/data/client.ts:2339-2497`
**Severity:** CRITICAL
**Tables affected:** `appointments`, `payments`, `reviews`
```typescript
// client.ts:2342-2347
const [apptsRes, paymentsRes, reviewsRes, patientsRes] = await Promise.all([
  supabase.from("appointments").select("*").eq("clinic_id", clinicId),
  supabase.from("payments").select("*").eq("clinic_id", clinicId).eq("status", "completed"),
  supabase.from("reviews").select("*").eq("clinic_id", clinicId),
  supabase.from("users").select("id, created_at").eq("clinic_id", clinicId).eq("role", "patient"),
]);
```
**Impact:**
- A clinic with 10,000 appointments fetches ALL 10,000 rows with ALL columns to the browser
- Supabase default limit is 1,000 rows per request -- this silently truncates results, producing **incorrect analytics** (wrong counts, wrong revenue totals)
- Appointments table has 27+ columns -- massive payload transferred to client
- All aggregation (daily counts, revenue sums, service popularity, heatmaps) is done client-side in JavaScript instead of SQL
- This function is called on the analytics/dashboard page -- loaded on every admin visit
**Remediation:**
- Use Supabase RPC functions to compute aggregations server-side (SUM, COUNT, GROUP BY)
- At minimum, restrict to a date range (e.g. last 6 months) and select only needed columns
- Move this to a server-side function to avoid shipping raw data to the browser
